post_text:
Dear GTSD Community,

Well, we did it! With your collaboration, patience, and diligence we completed the 19/20 school year. Thank you to everyone.

Summer Camp 2020. The NJ Department of Health (DOH) published guidelines for summer camps late yesterday. We are currently reviewing the guidelines to determine whether we can meet the requirements set forth by the DOH and offer summer camp beginning July 6th. We will provide additional information regarding Summer Camp later this week.

20/21 School Year. The NJ Department of Education intends to provide guidelines for Summer 2020 and for the 20/21 School Year later this month. We will review the guidelines upon receipt to determine the parameters within which are required to comply and will then reach out to parents and staff for suggestions.

Again, thank you. May you enjoy a restful, COVID-19 free summer break. Take care and I will be in touch as conditions warrant

post_text:
Dear Parents, Guardians, and Staff,

We made it to our much-anticipated Spring Break!

Our SMS Counselor Megan Deurring and Occupational Therapist Gayle Lewis developed another newsletter and coined a new descriptor for those of us who are parenting, teaching and working all at the same time: Paranorking! In it, they offer some strategies to occupy your children while you work from home. Please see The Sudden Era of Paranorking.pdf for tips and strategies.

Last week we instituted “catch up” days as a means to reduce stress and anxiety related to work completion. Parents, teachers, and students have indicated catch up days helped but additional revisions to our program may be needed. We will continue to address concerns, revise as necessary, and notify you in advance.

Again, thank you for your continued support and collaboration. Take care.

Chag samech and happy Easter to all.

Dear Parents, Guardians, and Staff,

As we monitor the COVID-19 outbreak locally and globally, it has become abundantly clear that we must continue to mitigate the spread of COVID-19 by practicing social distancing.

By an executive order from Governor Murphy directing, "All public, private, and parochial preschool programs, and elementary and secondary schools, including charter and renaissance schools, will be closed beginning on Wednesday, March 18, 2020, and remain closed as long as the Order remains in effect". We are closely monitoring the situation and reassessing the duration of this closure.

The District will continue to implement our telelearning plan in order to provide student instruction during this executive order. At this point, the reopening of school will be determined by Governor Murphy.

Take care.

The District will continue to implement our telelearning plan in order to provide student instruction during this executive order. At this point, the reopening of school will be determined by Governor Murphy.

Take care.

post_text:
Dear GTSD Family,

It is with great sadness that I report the passing of one of our beloved 8th grade students, Jennifer Costaesilva, and her mother Petrizzia. Jen along with her mother and father were traveling in Virginia yesterday when they were involved in a fatal automobile accident. Jen’s father remains hospitalized.

Jen was a wonderfully sweet girl, who had a sharp wit, intelligence, sense of humor, and insight beyond her years. She was a great friend to so many peers and was a bright light in their day. This is a great loss to the GTSD family.

Grief counselors will be available to meet with students, parents, and staff later this afternoon or tomorrow. Once scheduled, I will notify you of their availability. Obviously, we will practice social distancing in light of COVID-19.

I wil be in touch. Take care.

post_text: Today in the 4th grade science, the students earned free passes to the US National Parks by participating in a lesson on Environmental Stewardship. This lesson was made available through the National Parks Services and the United States Government. It is part of their Every Kid In A Park Program, which was started back in 2015. It allows all 4th grade students to gain free access to any of the national parks in the United States. The kids were engaged and motivated to keep practicing being better stewards for their schools, communities, homes, and environment. Great job 4th grade. Keep up the good work!

Without their support and generosity, we would not have been able to provide this increasingly rare opportunity for the students and community of Stewartsville. Enjoy some pictures of the Assembly!

post_text: SMS students participated in the American Legion 75th Annual George Diem Safety Essay Contest. The essay subject was "What Safety Means to Me" and was conducted in ELA classes. We are happy to announce that Keya G., 8th grade student, was the winner of the Greenwich Local Chapter. Each local chapter forwarded the winners to the Warren County Chairman where they were judged. I'm happy to say that Keya's essay also won 2nd place on the county level. CONGRATULATIONS Keya! You did an awesome Job. Also we would like to thank Charlie Henshaw, of the American Legion Greenwich Chapter for presenting the 1st place and 2nd place monetary awards to Keya at the SMS School.

post_text:
SMS - Congratulations to Sam S. for obtaining the Middle Level Representative on the Executive Board of Student Council for the State of New Jersey. Sam was running against 4 other students from other districts. With 50 of our students behind him on the campaign floor holding banners, posters, and cheering for him, they made quite an impact. Afterwards, Sam had to make a speech in front of hundreds of student council presidents in order to win their vote. We are thrilled to say that SAM WON! Congratulations and Sam will represent SMS with the high school students on this board. We are very proud of you and our active Student Council - Ms. Boyer and Ms. Gengaro
** A special thank you to Ms. G and Ms. Boyer our wonderful advisors for Student Council.

post_text:
SMS: Yesterday 50 members of our student council and members at large attended the NJASC January Conference. In addition to listening to an outstanding motivational speaker and award ceremony, students were able to attend workshops so that they could network with other students in the State of NJ in order to bring back new ideas for our school along with additional leadership skills.

WE ARE PROUD to say that SMS was awarded THE HONOR SCHOOL award for the 11th straight year. This is not easy to achieve because their are many requirements that your student council must meet. CONGRATULATIONS SMS STUDENT COUNCIL!

text:
GTSD - Employment Opportunity
ANTICIPATED Opening for Stewartsville Middle School Principal - Our PK-8 progressive district is seeking an experienced educator to lead a 255 pupil middle school educating students in grades 6-8.

*Position available on or about October 1, 2018.

*Salary commensurate with experience.

*Qualifications:
NJ Principal Certification;
Minimum 10-year teaching experience required - middle level preferred;
Minimum 3-year district leadership experience preferred;
Strong background in curriculum design and instructional strategies required;
Special education experience preferred.

Please send letter of interest, resume, and relevant certifications on or before July 30, 2018 to:

Maria Eppolite, Superintendent of Schools, Greenwich Township School District, 101 Wyndham Farm Boulevard, Stewartsville, NJ 08886

DISTRICT: Congratulations to Greenwich Township School District Alumni, Kwinton Adams who will graduate with 2 Degrees this Spring!

Post from PHS: Kwinton Adams, son of Annette Walters, and a senior at Phillipsburg High School, will be graduating from two institutions this spring. Kwinton will graduate from Warren County Community College with an Associate’s Degree in Liberal Arts on May 19, 2018 and will graduate on June 13, 2018 with his high school degree. Kwinton has worked diligently to achieve this goal. In addition to taking Dually Enrolled classes at PHS, he took summer courses at community colleges in order to receive his Associate’s Degree! Kwinton will attend Washington and Jefferson College in the fall with intentions to pursue medical school. This is just one of MANY fine examples of PHS graduates from the Class of 2018! Congratulations Kwinton!
